# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1919-cleveland-indians-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The **1894 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1894.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Baltimore Orioles as the pennant winner of the National League and the New York Giants as runner-up.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first Temple Cup on October 4 and ended with Game 4 on October 8.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants swept the Orioles, capturing their first Temple Cup.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the Temple Cup, following the end of the World's Championship Series with the demise of the American Association in 1891 and the one-off, split-season 1892 World's Championship Series.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place in the previous season and would be used until 1898.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring eight teams.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, also featuring eight teams.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Temple Cup took place between October 4 and October 8.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Makeshift stands built for remainder of the season, from August 18.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the start of the season, the Cincinnati Reds' home as League Park saw major changes.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] A new grandstand in what was left field was built, as well as an ampitheater.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The baseball diamond was shifted from the southeast corner of the lot to the southwest corner, with the original seating retained as right field seating.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The **1901 Cleveland Blues season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] It was the franchise's first in the majors, being one of the original franchises of the American League.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] Called the "Blues" or "Bluebirds", the team finished seventh out of eight teams.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The Cleveland Spiders were dissolved after winning only 20 games and losing 134 in the 1899 season along with the Louisville Colonels, Baltimore Orioles, and the Washington Senators, leaving the National League with eight teams to begin the 1900 season.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] As a result, 1900 marked the first year since 1886 during which the city of Cleveland did not have a team affiliated with Major League Baseball.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] During this time, Cleveland had a minor league baseball team, known as the Bluebirds or Blues due to their all-blue uniforms, which finished their season with a 63–73 record and finished sixth.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The American League became a major league before the 1901 season.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] As the American League made the jump to major league status, many players jumped ship, including Cy Young and Nap Lajoie, which led the National League to call them an "outlaw league" in November 1900.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] As the 1901 season came underway in April, and as the war between the two leagues erupted, the Cleveland franchise, now known as the Blues, began its first official season as a Major League Baseball team.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The Cleveland Blues played their first game of the season against the Chicago White Stockings on April 24, 1901.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] This was the first games in the history of the American League; three other games scheduled that day were rained out.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The starting lineup consisted of: Ollie Pickering (RF), Jack McCarthy (LF), Frank Genins (CF), Candy LaChance (1B), Bill Bradley (3B), Erve Beck (2B), Bill Hallman (SS), Bob Wood (C), and Bill Hoffer (P).
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] Hoffer allowed seven runs in the first two innings and the Blues failed to recover, as they lost the game 8–2, earning the first loss in American League history.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] In the second game of the season, Beck hit the first home run in American League history off pitcher John Skopec, but the Blues lost again, 7–3.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] On May 9, 1901, Earl Moore threw the first no-hitter in the history of the franchise and the American League.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The Blues lost to Chicago by a score of 4–2 despite allowing no hits.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] On May 23, Cleveland scored nine runs with the bases empty and two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning to beat Washington 14–13.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1902-cleveland-bronchos-season] The **1902 Cleveland Bronchos season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1902-cleveland-bronchos-season] The team, known during this season as the "Bronchos" (or "Broncos"), finished in fifth place in the American League with a record of 69–67, 14 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1902-cleveland-bronchos-season] In 1902, the National League's Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1902-cleveland-bronchos-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Indians, then known unofficially as the Bronchos and subsequently renamed the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1903-cleveland-naps-season] The **1903 Cleveland Naps season** was the third Major League Baseball season for the Cleveland American League team.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1903-cleveland-naps-season] After two seasons as the Bluebirds or Blues and also being called the Bronchos (or Broncos) in 1902, beginning with the 1903 season, the team was called the Naps in honor of star second baseman Nap Lajoie.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1903-cleveland-naps-season] The team finished third in the league with a record of 77–63, 15 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1904-cleveland-naps-season] The **1904 Cleveland Naps season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1904-cleveland-naps-season] The team finished fourth in the American League with a record of 86–65, 7½ games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1905-cleveland-naps-season] The **1905 Cleveland Naps season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1905-cleveland-naps-season] The team finished fifth in the American League with a record of 76–78, 19 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1906-cleveland-naps-season] The **1906 Cleveland Naps season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1906-cleveland-naps-season] The team finished third in the American League with a record of 89–64, 5 games behind the Chicago White Sox.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1919-cleveland-indians-season] The **1919 Cleveland Indians season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1919-cleveland-indians-season/1919-cleveland-indians-season] The team finished second in the American League with a record of 84–55, 3.5 games behind the Chicago White Sox.
